T1  - Liquidity of the CBOE Equity Options
AU  - VIJH, ANAND M.
Y1  - 1990/09/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1990.tb02431.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1157
EP  - 1179
VL  - 45
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1990.tb02431.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We examine the CBOE option market depth and bid-ask spreads. Absence of price effects surrounding large option trades suggests excellent market depth. However, bid-ask spreads for the CBOE options and the NYSE stocks are nearly equal, even though an average option is equivalent to less than half a stock plus borrowing. We explain this tradeoff between market depth and bid-ask spreads on the CBOE and the NYSE by differences in market mechanisms. We also show that the adverse-selection component of the option spread, which measures the extent of information-related trading on the CBOE, is very small.
ER  - 

